MS-900 Study Guide: Microsoft 365 Fundamentals

This study guide is designed to help you prepare for the MS-900: Microsoft 365 Fundamentals exam.
This exam measures your foundational knowledge of Microsoft 365 services and concepts, including cloud concepts, core Microsoft 365 services and pricing, security, compliance, and more.

Using this Study Guide: This is not intended to be a complete/exhaustive resource. These are high level points that can be used as guidance for studying.
For each point, my recommendation would be to spend 3-5 minutes in Microsoft Learn reading about the specifics of that point.

Concepts Covered:
Cloud Concepts (Cloud Computing Models, Cloud Benefits and Considerations, Types of Cloud Services)
Core Microsoft 365 Services and Concepts (Microsoft 365 Overview, Core Services, Microsoft 365 Apps)
Security, Compliance, Privacy, and Trust (Security Features, Identity and Access Management, Compliance Features)
Microsoft 365 Pricing, Licensing, and Support (Pricing Models, Licensing Options, Service Level Agreements, Support)
Key Definitions
Exam Tips

1. Cloud Concepts

Cloud Computing Models
Public Cloud: Cloud resources are owned and operated by a third-party cloud service provider like Microsoft Azure.
Private Cloud: Cloud infrastructure operated solely for one organization. May be managed internally or by a third party.
Hybrid Cloud: A combination of public and private clouds, enabling data and applications to be shared between them.

Cloud Benefits and Considerations
Scalability: Easily scale up or down based on demand.
Cost-effectiveness: Pay only for what you use (pay-as-you-go).
Security: Built-in security measures and compliance standards.
Elasticity: Rapid expansion and contraction of resources to meet demand.
Business Agility: Rapidly deploy applications and services.

Types of Cloud Services
IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service): Provides virtualized computing resources over the internet (e.g., Azure Virtual Machines).
PaaS (Platform as a Service): Provides a platform allowing customers to develop, run, and manage applications (e.g., Azure App Service).
SaaS (Software as a Service): Software applications provided over the internet (e.g., Microsoft 365 apps like Word, Excel, etc.).

2. Core Microsoft 365 Services and Concepts

Microsoft 365 Overview
Microsoft 365 is a subscription service that includes Office applications, intelligent cloud services, and security features to help organizations be more productive and collaborative.

Core Services
Microsoft Teams: A collaboration platform that combines workplace chat, video meetings, file storage, and application integration.
Exchange Online: A cloud-based email service that allows users to access their email, calendars, and contacts across devices.
SharePoint Online: A web-based platform used to store, organize, share, and access information from any device.
OneDrive for Business: A file-hosting service that allows users to store files and share them with others securely.

Microsoft 365 Apps
Office Suite (Word, Excel, PowerPoint, Outlook): Core productivity apps available as part of Microsoft 365.
Microsoft 365 Apps for Enterprise: A higher-tier offering that includes the latest Office applications plus additional services like OneDrive and Teams.

3. Security, Compliance, Privacy, and Trust

Security Features
Multi-factor Authentication (MFA): Adds an additional layer of protection by requiring more than just a password to access an account.
Conditional Access: Controls access based on specific conditions (e.g., device location, user role).
Advanced Threat Protection (ATP): Provides protection from malware, phishing, and other advanced threats.
Microsoft Defender for Office 365: Protects against cyber threats like phishing and business email compromise.

Identity and Access Management
Azure Active Directory (Azure AD): Microsoft's cloud-based identity and access management service. It helps users access apps and services securely.
Single Sign-On (SSO): Users log in once to access multiple applications without needing to authenticate each time.
Role-Based Access Control (RBAC): Allows administrators to manage permissions based on the roles of users within the organization.

Compliance Features
Compliance Manager: A tool for managing regulatory compliance.
eDiscovery: Allows organizations to search and extract data that may be relevant to legal or compliance investigations.
Information Protection: Helps ensure sensitive data is classified, labeled, and protected according to its importance.
Data Loss Prevention (DLP): Prevents accidental or malicious sharing of sensitive information.

4. Microsoft 365 Pricing, Licensing, and Support

Pricing Models
Subscription-Based Pricing: Microsoft 365 services are typically sold on a subscription basis (monthly or yearly).
Consumption-Based Pricing: Services such as Azure are billed based on usage.

Licensing Options
Microsoft 365 Business: Suitable for small and medium businesses (up to 300 users). Includes productivity apps and basic security features.
Microsoft 365 Enterprise: Designed for large organizations, offering enhanced security, compliance, and management capabilities.
Microsoft 365 Education: Tailored for educational institutions, offering tools and services to support teaching and learning.

Service Level Agreements and Support
Service Level Agreements (SLAs): Microsoft guarantees a certain level of uptime for its services, usually 99.9% or higher.
Support Options: Microsoft provides different support tiers depending on the subscription level, ranging from self-help resources to 24/7 phone support.

5. Key Definitions
Cloud Computing: The delivery of computing services—servers, storage, databases, networking, software—over the internet (“the cloud”).
SaaS (Software as a Service): A method for delivering software over the internet, typically on a subscription basis.
IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service): Virtualized computing resources over the internet.
PaaS (Platform as a Service): Cloud-based platform services that allow developers to build and manage applications.
Azure Active Directory (Azure AD): Microsoft’s cloud-based identity and access management system.
Multi-factor Authentication (MFA): An authentication method that requires the user to provide two or more verification factors to gain access.
Conditional Access: A tool to control user access to applications and services based on specific conditions.
Data Loss Prevention (DLP): A feature that helps prevent sensitive information from being shared outside the organization.
eDiscovery: The process of searching for and retrieving electronically stored information (ESI) for legal purposes.

6. Exam Tips:
Understand Key Cloud Concepts: Review cloud computing models, benefits, and Microsoft 365 service types (IaaS, PaaS, SaaS).
Focus on Microsoft 365 Core Services: Be familiar with the main services such as Exchange, SharePoint, OneDrive, and Teams.
Security & Compliance: Pay close attention to security services, compliance tools, and identity management within Microsoft 365.
Licensing & Pricing: Know the differences between Business and Enterprise offerings, and be aware of pricing models.
Hands-on Practice: Try using some of the services (e.g., set up a OneDrive account, experiment with SharePoint) to reinforce your understanding.
